Barack Obama will be the fourth U.S. president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth American president in history.
The diploma, medal and cheque for $1.4 million will be received, among other things, for exceptional efforts in strengthening world diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and will have a lot to do.
First, he visits the Nobel Institute, where for the first time he will meet the five members of the committee that, in October, chose him from 172 people and 33 organizations.
Afterwards, the presidential couple is scheduled to meet with Norway's King Harald V and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate with a ceremony at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive it, although the third to receive him in office.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the award, it will talk about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid such a subject, knowing that he is receiving the award as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts increased further with the dispatch of additional troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to mention.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, diploma and cheque for ten million Swedish kronor (approximately 24 million CZK).
He intends to donate them to charity, but has not yet decided to which particular organization.
During his full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet attended by the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude toward the prize.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling of not fully deserving it.
He also repeated several times that the award is not only for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he mentioned that it represents "a challenge to take action."
