USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comical that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the most intelligent man, as a diligent pupil repeats on the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his eagerly awaited Afghan approach, it proved to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only is the phrase "same as in Iraq" used several times in the same text, but he also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 declaration for his own statement: "A New Way Forward."
It was he himself who three years ago criticized Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from civil war. And he criticized that as "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences."
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so that today there is nothing to talk about Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, but objectively it left his successor in a much more favorable initial situation than might be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will be repeated.
Field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal. He, even in spite of traditional subordinate relationships, subjected the undecided riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but couldn't think of any better, so he at least deceived the general over 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic of Obama's entire strategy seems his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and complete this procedure in three years. The whole Obama doctrine raised more questions than the answers it offered.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is kept.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are accustomed to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, though formally established, will remain only a Potemkin village. Behind him will remain patriarchal tribal relations.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated by confused relations, made even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "actionable," a minimum goal of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama's strategy clashes because of his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to explode.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "return home soon", will perform some miracle here.
From the political point of view, setting the date of the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, since the Taliban will regard it as an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their constituents, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult choice: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to look for the answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphal withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that the presidential elections are three years away and that is why there is still a lot of time to find another strategy, if it turns out to be a total failure.
Goldman Sachs bank executives will no longer receive cash bonuses
Senior executives at U.S. bank Goldman Sachs will not receive the cash bonuses this year.
The entity announced it to react to harsh criticism of its salary practices.
The group of 30 senior managers will receive, instead of money, shares that cannot be sold for at least five years.
In addition, the shares may be withdrawn in the event that they have assumed excessive risks.
According to Reuters, Goldman Sachs thus became the leader in the effort to unite bonuses on Wall Street with long-term power.
