The problem is in the details, he added.
Goldman Sachs faced criticism after setting aside nearly $17 billion (nearly CZK 300 billion) for bonuses in the first three quarters of this year.
The total sum of bonuses in the entity for this year, according to Reuters, probably exceeds, despite the measure announced today, 20,000 million dollars.
High bonuses in the banking sector became, with the onset of the financial crisis, a sensitive issue in politics.
Britain announced Wednesday that it plans to tax at one time, with a fifty percent tax, bonuses for bankers exceeding 25,000 pounds (approximately 712,000 CZK).
France is also preparing similar measures.
This year women received Nobel Prizes in all categories except Physics.
Five women, which is a record number, received this year's Nobel Prizes in Stockholm today in Stockholm from King Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden, in specialized categories and in literature.
In addition to the four scientists, a German writer of Romanian origin, Herta Müller, was also among the winners.
The Nobel Prize in medicine was awarded to two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider, as well as her compatriot Jack Szostak for research in the field of chromosomes.
The Nobel Prize in chemistry was awarded to the Israeli Ada Jonath and the Americans Venkatraman Ramakrishna and Thomas Steitz for the explanation of the structure and function of ribosomes.
The last prize awarded, the Nobel Prize in Economics, was received by the American Elinor Ostrom and her compatriot Oliver Williamson for the analysis of an economic report.
The only specialized category, without a woman awarded, was Physics.
This award was received today by scientists Charles Kao for research in the field of optical cables, and George Smith with Willard Boyle for the invention of the CCD chip, which forms the basis of all digital cameras, faxes or telescopes.
Each laureate collected the diploma, the Nobel medal and the certificate of the money received.
This sum in each category is up to ten million Swedish kronor (approximately CZK 25 million).
In the case of several winners in each category, the prize is shared among themselves.
The traditionally most anticipated Nobel, the Peace Nobel, was received this afternoon in Oslo, Norway, by US President Barack Obama.
In his speech he acknowledged the controversy of having been awarded, since he is at the beginning of his career and is also at the head of a country that participates in two wars: in Iraq and Afghanistan.
To defend his policy he added, however, that in certain situations wars are essential to achieve peace, even if their price is high.
