The secret of splendor over Norway solved: the Russians tested a missile
A special luminous effect of unknown origin was observed over Norway.
The Russian Defense Ministry ended up acknowledging yesterday that near the borders with Norway it tested an intercontinental ballistic missile.
The launch failed again. The "Bulava" missile, previously intended to be the pride of the Russian military, is becoming the nightmare of Russian generals and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
Not even its repeated presence in missile tests has had the desired effect on the success of test flights.
Bulava, in most cases, did not fly out or there was a failure in the air.
In Russian newspapers they write of "Bulava" as "a missile that does not fly".
A missile that doesn't fly, but shines.
During this, the 13th test, no problems occurred at first.
At the end of the flight there were again technical problems in the aircraft.
The engine probably exploded in the third stage of the missile.
This time "Bulava" was launched from the nuclear submarine Dmitry Donskoy, which floated submerged in the White Sea.
This type of missile makes it possible to launch from a vessel that is moving and submerged at the same time.
That is why it is likely that the mysterious light over Norway, caused by an unidentified flying object, was actually the failed "Bulava".
The Norwegians did not hesitate from the first moment that it was a Russian missile.
The generals this time defend themselves by claiming that one cannot simply speak of a failure.
The first two stages of the missile endured and the breakdown occurred in the third.
In the above cases the engines broke down immediately in the first stage.
Although none of the launches went completely without errors, according to the management of the Ministry of Defense only six of the thirteen were failed.
The success of almost fifty percent fills the generals with optimism and that is why they continue to affirm that "Bulavá" will one day fly without problems and that it will even manage to carry up to ten nuclear hypersonic blocks, whose maximum total weight is 1.15 tons.
