The pneumococal vaccine will be free and voluntary
The pneumococal vaccine from January will put an end to the usual customs.
As a first vaccine it should be free for families and at the same time voluntary.
However, there are already opinions that the mandatory vaccine would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of the free pneumococcal vaccine are complete.
The Institute of Medicines is already setting maximum prices for vaccines, which will be covered by insurance companies.
Experts are also already clear about this in the vaccination procedure.
The new vaccine
Free vaccinations for children born in August
From January, children born since August 2 of last year will be able to receive the pneumococal vaccine free of charge.
The condition is not having received a single dose of the vaccine before.
Those who started the vaccine last year or earlier have to cover other doses of the vaccine as well.
The first dose of the vaccine must be received between the third and fifth month of age of the child.
Last year, a quarter of families voluntarily stopped vaccinating their children against pneumococci.
Parents however paid for a dose 1600 kroner and more.
Four doses are needed to vaccinate younger children.
Experts generally estimate that insurance companies will spend 300 to 450 thousand crowns annually on vaccines.
However they will save on treatment, which is needed for unvaccinated children.
So far the state has spent about 500,000 annually for the entire vaccination of children.
Covered vaccination was initiated by the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococcus is the cause of otitis media, but also of serious infections including meningitis and septicemia.
According to research in hospitals, 28 children no older than 10 years of age die from pneumococal infections in our country every year.
In addition to the Czech Republic, pneumocal vaccine cover in children was introduced in approximately 40 countries.
Will the vaccine be mandatory?
However, at the same time there are opinions that this vaccine could be mandatory in the future.
From January you must be covered by insurance companies and voluntary.
The mandatory vaccine would be better, said Rudolf Kalovský, the head of the Nahlas civic association.
Their association has been spreading pneumococal vaccines for a long time.
The experts at an international conference, in which our association participated, were not completely satisfied with the fact that we have the voluntary vaccine.
It's not completely ideal.
On the other hand we are happy, to achieve at least this.
I think this is the path we now have to take, Kalovský said.
The Ministry of Health, however, does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination procedure.
At this time we don't think about it at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Voluntary vaccine has its downsides, doctors say
The president of the society of pediatricians Odborná společnost praktických dětských lékařů Hana Cabrnochová recognizes that the voluntary vaccine has its disadvantages.
If all children would receive the vaccine, it will be possible to reason about reducing the number of doses. "In the situation, when the vaccine costs such a high amount, we relatively understand the political decision to have started vaccination as a volunteer," says Cabrnochová.
Experts expect that starting next year more than 80 percent of young parents will let their babies vaccinate against pneumococci.
The pneumococal vaccine is a big change also because as the first vaccination in children is covered by health companies, not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend more money on prophylaxis, only to save on treatment, Cabrnochová explains.
Doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves.
However, pediatricians are concerned about buying vaccines.
Previously, vaccines had to be bought by insurance companies and distributed to doctors, just as when the state gives them other vaccines.
Some MPs, however, were afraid that insurance companies might "take the money out of health insurance".
Doctors will therefore have to buy the vaccines and wait, until they are paid for by insurance companies.
It is estimated that pediatricians will invest 40,000 a month in vaccines, which is a remarkable sum.
It won't be easy, says Cabrnochová.
