Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Peking University's Institute of Demographic Research, said central government officials have recently been debating even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one spouse is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to incentivize more births.
Almost overnight, signs ordering families to have only one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who would be suitable to have a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city government sent family planning officials and volunteers to visit couples in their homes and slip leaflets under doors.
It has also promised to provide emotional and financial guidance to those who have chosen to have more than one child.
Family planning officials say the response has been very unoverwhelming.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai say they saw a moderate increase in applications from couples wanting a second child after the campaign launched, more urban districts do not indicate any change.
Huinan Township, with a population of 115,000, for example, is still receiving only four to five applications per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that, despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to only reach about 165,000, slightly higher than in 2009 but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee at Caolu Township in Shanghai, said financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want more children.
They want to give the best to their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and are legally entitled to do so.
But like many Chinese, they have only the insufficient health and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social safety net, they argue, that option would be irresponsible.
People in the West incorrectly see the one-child policy as a matter of rights, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child.
Yes, they are robbing us of the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just a political issue.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their doubts.
Wang, the human resources manager, said she wants an only child because she was too: "We were the center of our families and we were used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to taking care of others and we really don't want to take care of others. "
Chen Zijian, 42, who owns a translation agency, explained it more bluntly.
For parents with two middle-class careers that lower the birth rate, he said, it's about being successful enough to be selfish.
People in their 20s and 30s grew up watching their parents' struggle during the early days of China's experiment with capitalism and don't want that kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child requires a lot of parental time, he said.
A mother has to give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are issues of space, "they have to remodel their apartment," and the strategic "has to have a curriculum prepared for the best daycare centers when the child is 9 months old."
