UN panel outlines plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, so far characterized by defiant stances and mutual recriminations, captured renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that envisions ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations shouldering most of the burden in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important breakthrough in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders set to arrive in Copenhagen next week.
Drafted by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not talk about how much money rich countries would give poor ones to tackle global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit to global temperature rise that policymakers would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture."
It shows the outlines for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by 25 to 45 percent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce theirs over the same period by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also spurred talks on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Still, Friday featured the same kind of verbal fireworks that dominated talks last week.
U.S. special climate envoy Todd Stern rejected claims calling for mandatory cuts in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to voluntary cuts from major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is taking a harder line with China than Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States is not going to make a deal without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, said Stern, who also lamented that the text did not do enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern's comments came an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei said the top U.S. climate negotiator lacked "common sense," or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the U.S. would not help China economically cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, fault lines have erupted both within the developing world, and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is as much to save individual economies as it is to save the planet, with China and the United States clashing over their respective obligations, while poorer nations insist that the world's twenty-four most influential countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the bravest action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that major powers are arguing over who should pay for the expenses to limit greenhouse gases, even as vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in trying to contain the big emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is developing, said Ulate, who also works as regional advisor on climate change for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated they would continue to push for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, even though most major participants say the talks will at most produce a political settlement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page preliminary treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who is leading international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said the push by small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process," in part because they are now unified and demand action from emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most exceptional issues before heads of government can close a deal.
High-level officials, including Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Vice Minister, descended from the planes and rushed into the halls of the Bella Center, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, so they could narrow down the claims to be arbitrated over the next week.
The sheer mess of the meeting (where every day 13,000 people enter and leave the convention center, guitar-playing activists put on nightly shows mocking the countries they say are selling, and pass preliminary proposals from hand to hand rather than via mail), poses a challenge.
Intensity only builds: almost all the key ministers are here at the moment, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
"We're entering the major leagues," said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Conservation International's vice president for global policy.
The heavyweights are coming.
