Managerial revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of employees adhering to "values" determined from above as before it was a question of imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to strategies to conquer markets... Although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that have no relation to customer preference factors is regularly repeated.
A demobilization of employees can end in deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R+D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have a proactive conduct and a prospective vision"; It needs a commitment from employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of authoritarian management.
For this reason, we called for a management revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the company's concerns as well as the client.
Internal opinion polls are relatively useful
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, incite managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, faced with a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially ... what they always did! B989
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Since they come from the great schools of engineering, they interpret psychology mechanistically.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the old behavioral theory that the American "neurosciences" recently revived, and which the Institutes of Studies and the media widely disseminated behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "commands" (sic) of executive engagement, recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management posture, unadapted to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, involves adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into every reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make part of their dreams, ambitions and projects come true.
Today, only studies from Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
By identifying and measuring mobilization factors, business managers can monitor, forecast and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resource management "in place".
In this way, they create a favorable terrain for the organized development of strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo Speech: For "Just War" Obama Receives Praise from the Right
On Friday, the American right, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize winner defended the concept of "just war" against America's enemies, hailed Obama's speech on Thursday.
Conservatives, who had discredited Obama's Oct. 9 award, this time applauded the president's speech, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate during the 2008 election.
"I loved what she said," Ms. Palin, a leading right-wing figure in the Republican Party, told USA Today, adding that she herself had addressed the issue of war "sometimes necessary" in her recently published memoir.
In my opinion, war is certainly the last thing the Americans want to be forced to do, but it is necessary.
The terrorists must be stopped, he observed.
Obama, who inherited his predecessor George W. Bush's two wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, dedicated himself Thursday in Oslo to justifying the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 more troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another Obama adversary, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really good, rejoiced the former speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential remarks.
At times, the speech seemed very historic to me, Gingrich said during an interview on "The Takeaway" radio show.
The former elected representative, who some consider as a possible candidate for the Republican inauguration for the 2012 presidential elections, was pleased to hear "a leftist president" when he reminded the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not deliver a peace prize if the use of force did not exist."
According to Michael Gerson, author of George W. Bush's speeches and current reporter at the Washington Post, Obama delivered "a very American speech."
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world," as he "always does," he "spoke like an American president" by reminding Europeans "who live in a bubble of security that they did not create and who do little to preserve it," Gerson said.
Among the few unconvinced right-wingers, a Bush-era hawk, former U.N. Ambassador John Bolton, called the speech "monotonous, pretentious and uninspired" on the National Review Online website.
To the president's left, Democratic Rep. Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When we cover war with the notion of justice, it is easy to justify the slaughter of innocents, he warned.
However, the center-left press praised the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while still believing Obama received the Nobel Prize prematurely, called his speech a "blockbuster" especially for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech "should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions in the fight against conflict, poverty and oppression," the Californian newspaper enthused.
Obama "delivered the speech that was necessary," the New York Times said, calling it "both somber and edifying."
