As these become slippery quickly, the salted vehicle starts as soon as the temperature drops below two degrees.
In case of emergency, the police can also call them.
The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa hallae looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 1.50 meters tall that ran on the two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this wouldn't have been something special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's journal Science.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was located in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangaea at the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, propagation and characteristics of early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we have found in a day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is something unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis team member of the Natural History Museum of Utah.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they gathered in total the remains of five specimens.
A find confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional find: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only single fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts don't entirely share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared approximately 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: carnivorous theropods among which are Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velociraptor and also birds, quadrupedal sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and herbivorous Ornithischia (saurians with bird pelvis).  to which belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and colleagues, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa hallae the researchers found indications of air pockets, such as those also possessed by the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa Hallae's case, too, the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of later giant sauropods also possessed air pockets and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known so far lived in South America, researchers deduce that saurians first emerged there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lineages initially separated and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single land mass, the supercontinent Pangaea.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa the remains of two other theropods not very close related.
All three cannot descend from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We think there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Naturally, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group to dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
Their opinion could give a distorted picture, because many dinosaur fossils are still preserved in South America, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to dominant Mesozoic terrestrial vertebrates remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic dinosaurs expanded throughout the world and many new species developed, while kinship became extinct on the border of the Triassic towards the Jurassic.
Success stories were not eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Success stories aren't always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact halted the rise of a group of species, which had also already evolved in the Triassic and since then led a miserable existence: mammals.
