New Silicon Valley
For many years, it was regarded as a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenograd, one of Moscow's ten districts, was in the Soviet Union a heavily guarded site for secret weapons research.
Today, the community of 216,000 inhabitants, located 37 kilometers from the center of Moscow, is considered the "Russian Silicon Valley".
Here are important research and production centers of micro and nanoelectronics.
Since September 2008, representatives of Selenograd have contacted the Riedberg scientific headquarters in Frankfurt, university institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Center (FIZ).
There were several mutual visits and now, on Wednesday, Selenograd and Riedberg sign in Frankfurt a "Protocol of close collaboration".
Moscow Deputy Mayor Juri Rosljak and Selengrad Mayor Anatoly Smirnov led the Russian delegation; for Frankfurt signed the head of planning services Edwin Schwarz.
In 2010, representatives of the FIZ and directors of small and medium-sized enterprises of the natural sciences research center will travel to a seminar in Selenograd.
Scientific exchange
This is an ongoing scientific exchange.
But it also addresses commercial relations.
FIZ companies will have the possibility to set foot in the growing Russian market.
In return, Russian scientific companies want access to contracts in Germany.
Selenograd is home to important Russian companies and research institutes.
These include, for example, the Moscow Institute of Electronic Technology, the large consortiums Sitronics and Rossijskaja Elektronika.
The community was founded in 1958 as the so-called "Socialist Planning City" for weapons research.
Selenograd (literally translated as "Green City") got its name from the forested mountain landscape, in which research facilities were settled.
Stuttgart brakes
The Stuttgart Dimension 21 is not placed high enough at all.
For the supporters of the project it is simply "the new heart of Europe".
The law so. S21 is much more than the downsizing of a railway station, more than a monstrous construction project, which will plunge the capital of the Banden-Württemberg region into a decade of chaos of hopeless construction sites.
Stuttgart 21 grew out of the spirit of the 1980s.
Terminals with rails, which end in the middle of the city, were considered at that time engineering fossils of the nineteenth century, which acted as brakes on modern rail traffic, since formerly it took an enormous amount of time to hook the locomotives from back to front.
Roll, stop in its tracks continue the journey; But that is how it must be done.
And that's why the terminals had to disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart: a way station, which is located approximately halfway through the trans-European lines between Paris and Budapest/Bratislava; hence the slogan of "Heart of Europe".
The S21 will really be started, even though the visions of the 80s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious designers have known that in the Hessian and Bavarian capitals it is almost priceless to implement the reduction.
The railway terminals of course do not have more problems of entry and exit, since there are reversible locomotives with tractor unit and driver's trolley at both ends.
However: Stuttgart 21 including the new section built by ICE to Ulm will already be started.
Federal and communal politicians have arranged it that way.
The railroad continues, also because the risks of the Republic's large individual infrastructure projects are borne by the taxpayer and not by the State.
From the urban point of view, the project is still justified to some extent.
New urban space is created, provided with many green areas, probably from the designer's computer-generated graphics.
For the rail transport system, the S21 is harmful.
The way station and road support are intended for the transport of people, which was attributed to the enormous growth typical of the 1980s.
At that time there was no competition from low-cost flights.
But modern transport policy must first be concerned with strengthening freight transport, since rail transport is considerably greener than that carried out by trucks on the roads.
However, the new sections under construction are not good for freight trains due to the intense gradients.
Even more serious is that the S21 also indirectly affects many other railway projects.
More than six billion euros must be buried in the Zuavos.
That's the official figure.
Experts consider that it is more realistic between ten and fifteen billion.
It is certain that in the next decade the money will be lacking in other crossings and narrow passages in the network.
A total of sixty major projects are on the list of the Ministry of Transport.
One of the most important is the extension of more than 180 kilometers of long rails through the Rhine Valley.
Since 1987 the route has been built at a slow pace.
It would be urgent here to step on the accelerator properly.
However, the S21 acts as a brake.
The stretch of the Rhine Valley will be the bottleneck for international freight transport: through the heart of Europe.
