Dream worlds
In the waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
It is not only in the case of the mentally ill and drug addicts that the boundaries between imagination and reality vanish.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can surrender unhindered to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, whoever experiences sleep-like states during wakefulness, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often considered in the modern Western world to be crazy or a drug addict, or at least a maniac.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or drugged.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, sometimes blur the boundaries between dream, madness and reality.
Dream-modified states of alert consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although triggers and effects can be distinguished, one can refer to similar processes the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castañeda, the states of shamanic possession, and psychoses and hallucinations.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain – especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine – has been derailed and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disturbed.
During schizophrenic psychosis, complex hallucinations and crazed thoughts often appear.
Gravity no longer has power over him
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of sleep in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness with dream states", for Sigmund Freud, sleep was even "a psychosis, with all the nonsense, crazy formations, and mirages of it".
It is the fall of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book figure.
His body is two-dimensional and outrageously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over him, he is floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, grimacing red as blood, misshapen, gnashing their teeth.
They are chasing him, kicking him with heavy, flaming boots, throwing him against the walls, he feels the pains all over his body.
Shrill and evil voices echo from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. rips two cables from the stereo, ties them to form a hangman's knot, and fixes them on a hook in the ceiling.
He climbs on a horn and puts the knot around his neck.
Salta.
The rope is released.
Let it serve as a lesson!, shout the voices in a chorus that bursts his eardrums, "Go to the clinic and have them cure you!"
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychoses, the last one two years ago, the first nearly 20 years ago.
The cause that produced it was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, takes medication, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
About one percent of the population falls ill at least once in their lifetime from schizophrenia; In psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most frequent illness after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outer and inner worlds, and fall into a state of overexcitement that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationship disorders, or persecution mania.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the floodgates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centred, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the general psychiatry clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time he enters into a passive role, as in a dream, feels overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
That is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is."
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, distancing from experience takes place in reality.
For researchers, it is still unknown why our brain makes jokes.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can lead anyone to temporarily lose touch with reality.
But not everyone develops a psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes there are also other determining factors.
Researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
"We suspect that the brain's neural maturity is affected early in development, such as through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy," Fuchs explains.
But it remains unknown how this alteration of the neural system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when there is already a previous disposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can provoke psychosis, as they interfere with the brain's transmitting system.
When the brain warms up
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer with their hallucinations and take very expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says psychology professor Erich Kasten, from Lübeck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been compiling reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analysed the results in the book Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf (The Unreal World in Our Head), published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychoses, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, along with psychic disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depression, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's and head trauma.
Surprisingly and under certain conditions, the brains of healthy people also suffer hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are made up of memories that are normally repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or poorly inhibited; when our brain heats up, but also when there is a lack of stimuli.
Drugs can cause this state in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, lovesickness or other exceptional brain states.
