Here are some snapshots.
About Albert Camus: "In its pages I discovered that the Mediterranean was not a sea, but a spiritual, almost physical impulse, the same that I felt without giving it a name: pleasure against fateful destiny, morality without guilt and innocence without any god."
On Samuel Beckett: "Nihilist, allegorical Christian, he wrote what he had in his blood, not in his intellect, between impotence and ignorance, with a dazzling, meaningless poetic humor, like the blade of the knife that almost killed him."
On Graham Greene: "Our man was abducted by this woman with a passion that lasted thirteen years, in whose flesh he combined the emotion of adultery with the pleasure of remorse, a spiritual privilege that consisted in reaching heaven through the path of perdition."
About James Joyce: "The 'Ulysses' was published in Paris in 1922 by Sylvia Beach. It is one of the eight-thousand-meter peaks of universal literature, which must be climbed up the north wall, from which the best mountaineers fall again and again."
On William Faulkner: "He was a weird guy.
Of himself, sometimes he said that he was heir to a county landowner and sometimes that he was the son of a black woman and a crocodile.
