On Louis-Ferdinand Céline: "This writer picked up the demented cry launched from a bridge by that character of Munich to carry its echo to the bottom of the night of the twentieth century in his literary form and did so on a journey fleeing from himself and invoking posterity with a violent speech to worms."
About Dorothy Parker: "One day she got down on her knees and prayed, 'Dear God, I beg you to stop writing like a woman.'"
About Joseph Conrad: "On his grave were engraved these verses of Spenser: 'Sleep after effort, / after storm the harbor, / rest after war, / after life long pleases death."
On Virginia Wolf: "In the luggage he also brought his depressions.
The husband accepted with all normality that she told him that Edward VII spied her among the azaleas or that the birds sang in Greek.
There has never been the case of a man so patient and in love with a neurotic whose literary talent was ahead of her madness."
On Pio Baroja: "What did Martin-Santos do but try to inoculate Joyce in Baroja?
What did Benet try but to pass Baroja by Faulkner's weapons?
What did Cela do but abduct that man's fame to serve as his own pedestal?"
