Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As happened with the ABS anti-lock brakes and will happen with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they already are in all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a grace period is set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, by the way they work, it can also help avoid many rear-end collisions.
What the emergency braking assistant does is increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the stomp that the driver gives.
But it doesn't always keep that pressure going until the end.
According to a study carried out by the manufacturer of car components Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not reached the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, demands the maximum to the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater – it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided – when the so-called intelligent emergency braking system becomes popular.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting lightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is unavoidable, the device exerts maximum effort to the brakes to minimize damage.
