In these days of storms and accidents, not only car workshops win.
Every day thousands of cars that have suffered an accident are towed to a workshop, where an expert must evaluate the damage suffered and what the repair cost will be.
No claim is the same, and calculating parts costs and labor time can be a long and complicated task.
Manually calculating the cost of a repair of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including parts and labor, can take two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer tools it would be a matter of minutes
Therefore, almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
Providers of claims valuation and maintenance services and solutions collect the information provided to them by manufacturers, and then develop it and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the North American group Solera, is the leading firm; 80% of the valuations are made with their products.
The other firms competing in the field of valuation and information tools on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by manufacturers is far from easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, in Spain they work with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with information in different formats.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, to the point that in the last five years more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the previous fifteen.
As soon as a new car goes on the market, these companies get to work.
It is a very arduous task, because you have to catalog each of the thousands of parts of the vehicle and enter its price.
In addition, a "smart" graphic image is made of each model where different parts of tourism can be "punctured".
If it is a sell-out model, the work can be ready in a week if the process goes very fast.
If it's a minority car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models they have information about Porsche, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini, for example.
As for the mobile fleet that circulates, they exceed 99%.
To carry out the documentation work and the elaboration of the databases, Audatex has eight centers spread around the world (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them is specialized in specific brands.
The national headquarters are in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually experts in mechanics) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros per year in developing these databases.
2.5 million pieces of data are included each month, and customers receive updates every other day.
The elaboration of this enormous flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and offer varied products.
The most frequent use focuses on repair and maintenance, but depending on which countries there are also tools for managing scrapping parts or to calculate the market or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of those used in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer it in our country, but it does in the United States.
In view of the products offered by Audatex it is easy to get an idea of the type of support they can provide to professionals in the sector.
This company offers ten different tools, being the flagship product AudaPlus, the standard solution for claims valuation, intended for surveyors.
It includes cars, motorcycles and light or heavy commercial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the paint scales.
This tool is paid according to use, for each rating.
The highest cost is 5.75 euros, for customers who use it little, a maximum of ten times a month.
Then each insurance company, which performs thousands of appraisals, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the total identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it left the assembly line only with its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle windows, and AudaSubastas is a service open to the professional sector on the internet that allows bidding on vehicles declared total loss.
Its statistics service is very useful to identify trends, perform geodemographic analysis or know the deviations by brands or models.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a certain brand have passed through the workshop due to breakdowns or how many have suffered serious accidents in a certain period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tools.
It sells, among others, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for experts and also provides digital images, access to parts or official prices and times of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa group founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damages, breakdowns or maintenance of the car
